isting errors catch UnsupportedFeature. I wonder if using ClassLoader.loadClass could help, but that involves dynamic loading too, which complicates things.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring Class Loading Patterns**\\n\\nI'm wondering whether it really isn't open-ended since it loads known classes from a specific jar. The Native Image doesn’t support that, but the developer rules suggest using a dynamic class loading pattern and catching exceptions in those cases. So, should I use Class.forName? That's direct reflection, which complicates matters. Yet, a public API test might not require it. Perhaps a good approach would be to combine a public API test with a fresh class loader initialization to verify legacy class calls.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing class initialization**\\n\\nI'm looking into whether the active class may not have tests. The test class imports HttpAuthenticator and calls a method that triggers the static initializer, hitting the logging line. I think the class initializes when it’s actively used, which is before executing selectAuthScheme. There’s no other active usage, so it works in the standard JVM run. \\n\\nI notice that the report says attempts are 0 for active, which is good. Now, I need to write a few tests and import the necessary auth classes.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_YnPsK125pZ09gFW4noNXb7KG|fc_009e3a7b715f7312016a048c02c48c8191b7c055077c1e6963", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge8/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/commons-httpclient/commons-httpclient/3.0/main/extracted/org/apache/commons/httpclient/auth/NTLMScheme.java", "limit": 130}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 8708, "output": 962, "cacheRead": 17408, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 27078, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "times